The paper discusses a method for generating appropriate motions for robots working in cluttered environments, which is a common problem in robotics. The use of conditional Generative Adversarial Networks (cGANs) for motion generation is a popular approach in robotics and falls under the category of machine learning (cs.AI). The paper also involves computer vision techniques for object detection and localization, which falls under the category of computer vision (cs.CV). The proposed method is evaluated on a real-robot experiment, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The paper also involves optimization techniques for searching the latent space of the trained cGANs, which falls under the category of machine learning and optimization (cs.LG, cs.SY).
